DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(82)90046-0
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199682900460
AB  - This paper makes a distinction between supply (export) specialization and demand (import) specialization, both of which can occur between activity sectors or inside them. It shows that intra-industry export specialization mostly characterized high-wage countries whereas low-wage nations tended to achieve inter-industry export specialization. Intra-industry import specialization, on the other hand, was the rule everywhere except in the very low-wage countries. Finally, the drift to intra-industry export specialization slowed down from 1970 to 1973 as compared to 1959–1970 inside (but not outside) the EEC.
